{
  "Remainder & Factor Theorems": "",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "",
  "Using the Remainder Theorem, what is the remainder when f(x) = 2x¬≥ + 5x ‚ąí 3 is divided by (x ‚ąí 2)?": "",
  "By the Remainder Theorem, the remainder is f(2) = 2(8) + 5(2) ‚ąí 3 = 16 + 10 ‚ąí 3 = 23.": "",
  "What is the remainder when f(x) = 3x‚ĀĶ ‚ąí 2x¬≤ + 7 is divided by (x + 2)?": "",
  "Dividing by (x + 2) means c = ‚ąí2. Compute f(‚ąí2) = 3(‚ąí32) ‚ąí 2(4) + 7 = ‚ąí96 ‚ąí 8 + 7 = ‚ąí97.": "",
  "What is the remainder when f(x) = x‚Āī ‚ąí 1 is divided by (x ‚ąí 1)?": "",
  "By the Remainder Theorem, the remainder is f(1) = 1‚Āī ‚ąí 1 = 0. This also tells us (x ‚ąí 1) is a factor of x‚Āī ‚ąí 1.": "",
  "What is the remainder when f(x) = 4x¬≤ ‚ąí 3x + 5 is divided by (x ‚ąí 1)?": "",
  "By the Remainder Theorem, the remainder is f(1) = 4(1)¬≤ ‚ąí 3(1) + 5 = 4 ‚ąí 3 + 5 = 6.": "",
  "What is a 'depressed polynomial' in the context of polynomial division?": "",
  "A depressed polynomial is the quotient obtained when dividing a polynomial by one of its linear factors. Its degree is one less than the original, and it can be further analyzed to find remaining roots.": "",
  "What is meant by 'reducing the degree' of a polynomial when finding roots?": "",
  "Once a root r is found, we factor out (x ‚ąí r) using synthetic division to obtain a quotient polynomial of one lower degree. We then apply root-finding methods to this simpler polynomial to find remaining roots.": "",
  "What is the relationship between the Remainder Theorem and the Factor Theorem?": "",
  "The Factor Theorem is a direct consequence of the Remainder Theorem. Since the remainder when dividing by (x ‚ąí c) equals f(c), a remainder of zero (i.e., f(c) = 0) means (x ‚ąí c) divides evenly, making it a factor.": "",
  "A pharmacist models a drug concentration in mg/L as C(t) = t¬≥ ‚ąí 6t¬≤ + 11t ‚ąí 6, where t is hours after administration. She tests t = 1 and finds C(1) = 0. After dividing out (t ‚ąí 1), what is the depressed polynomial?": "",
  "Synthetic division of t¬≥ ‚ąí 6t¬≤ + 11t ‚ąí 6 by (t ‚ąí 1): bring down 1; 1¬∑1 = 1, ‚ąí6+1 = ‚ąí5; 1¬∑(‚ąí5) = ‚ąí5, 11+(‚ąí5) = 6; 1¬∑6 = 6, ‚ąí6+6 = 0. The depressed polynomial is t¬≤ ‚ąí 5t + 6 = (t ‚ąí 2)(t ‚ąí 3).": "",
  "A city planner models a drainage function as D(x) = 2x‚Āī ‚ąí 5x¬≥ ‚ąí 4x¬≤ + 15x ‚ąí 6, where x is a flow rate parameter. If x = 1/2 is a root, what is the depressed polynomial after dividing by (x ‚ąí 1/2)?": "",
  "Synthetic division with c = 1/2 on coefficients 2, ‚ąí5, ‚ąí4, 15, ‚ąí6: bring down 2; (1/2)(2) = 1, ‚ąí5+1 = ‚ąí4; (1/2)(‚ąí4) = ‚ąí2, ‚ąí4+(‚ąí2) = ‚ąí6; (1/2)(‚ąí6) = ‚ąí3, 15+(‚ąí3) = 12; (1/2)(12) = 6, ‚ąí6+6 = 0. Quotient: 2x¬≥ ‚ąí 4x¬≤ ‚ąí 6x + 12.": ""
}